First Day of Classes

Fall 2020 Course Design Plans

As faculty determine their new course structures, they are reporting them here. Check back regularly for updates.

  • All Fall courses at WSU will be either HYB (hybrid), or IIE (fully online).
  • HYB might include limited in-person instruction, some synchronous online engagement (with participants meeting at the same time), and/or asynchronous content delivery (with participants engaging the materials independently). There are no additional fees for HYB courses.
  • Use the search function below to see how much content is online or in-person, whether there are synchronous expectations or asynchronous expectations, and whether testing will be in-person or online.

Once you have selected your fall schedule, enter your course information: CRN, Course number, Course name, OR Instructor. Select “All Fields” in the drop down menu, or select specific fields to narrow your search. To see all entries, simply enter a blank search.

                  Honors Research and Creative Activity Seminar

                  • 485
                  • (CRN: 17232)

                  • Instructor:

                    Nicole Woods
                  • nikki.keenewoods@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Optional in-person content delivery, with asynchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    Students who complete this course have familiarity with inquiry and research conceptualization — the process of investigating an area of interest. Students get experience formulating independent research projects, strategizing an appropriate methodology/approach, drafting abstracts and personal statements appropriate for grant or fellowship proposals, and working in interdisciplinary peer review groups. The student should plan to meet remotely during times of increasing cases of COVID-19 via Zoom or teleconference. In-person meetings may occur according to county health and social distancing guidelines.

                  • kurt.reding@wichita.edu

                  Statics (TR 11am and MW 5:35pm)

                  • AE223
                  • (CRN: 12749, 13400)

                  • Instructor:

                    Roy Myose
                  • ROY.MYOSE@WICHITA.EDU

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Fully remote, synchronous delivery (HYB) - not a true hybrid course

                  • Testing Type

                    Required online testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    (13 August Update - no other updates will be posted on this site - see course Blackboard site for the latest course plans) Due to the increased RATE of positive cases (e.g., see here: https://sedgwickcounty.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/7b2b4364a5fa4ba3a015d52450acfe0d), the course design plan had to be changed (from the earlier June announcement). Please note that the description below are the tentative plans as of late July and is subject to drastic change (as has already happened once before), though PLANS will be made relatively firm by 14 August. (Plans are not the same as what will actually transpire so be prepared for potential changes during the semester, including changes to the grading structure.)

                    Students must have reliable high speed internet access, laptop or desktop computer which runs genuine Microsoft Office software, a video camera (internal or external), a microphone (internal or external), Zoom video conferencing software, and Chrome or Firefox browser for Blackboard access. Microsoft Office – Excel will be used to access the SYNCHRONOUS online quizzes during class days & times and the online comprehensive final exam on the university assigned date & time. After opening the quiz (or final exam) Excel file, you must enter your WSU ID before starting the quiz (or final exam). You must save the file on your computer (not GoogleDocs) BEFORE submitting it from Blackboard. Note that the file must be saved BEFORE the Blackboard "submit" command button. Content delivery will be a combination of synchronous meetings using Zoom and pre-recorded lectures & example problem solutions.

                    There will be an in-person test over prerequisite material (called a pre-test) during the second week of classes. Since classroom seating is limited, the in-person pre-test will be given to two (or three) groups on two (or three) different days. If you come to the in-person test without your own mask or face covering, you will not be allowed entry into the classroom which will result in a score of zero for the pre-test. The university has no exception to this rule about masks and having a health (or other) issue for not wearing a mask will not provide an excuse (see next paragraph for substitution option, but only available if arranged in advance). Limited seating in the classroom means that it will not be possible to find a seat with a different group (i.e. date) than the one you are assigned to. The in-person pre-test is closed book, closed notes, and only a basic scientific calculator (non-programmable / non-graphing) is allowed. Once again, a mask that you bring on your own plus a basic scientific calculator (non-graphing / non-programmable type) are required and you must come on the assigned date and time.

                    The pre-test is an important and required in-person element, so this class is a hybrid format course. Dr. Myose realizes that there may be individuals in the at-risk health category or live with family members who are at-risk. (Dr. Myose himself has multiple at-risk health issues.) Such students MUST obtain approval from the Office of Disability Services (contact ODS at disability.services@wichita.edu NOT Dr. Myose) that an exception is needed for an alternative to the in-person test due to health reasons. (If you are already at-risk, seek ODS approval NOW, not during the first week of classes.) The declaration / request must be made by the end of the first week, well in advance of the pre-test date. [Exception: if you feel sick on the day of the pre-test, please do not endanger your classmates or Dr. Myose (because if he becomes sick and the department cannot find a substitute, the course may be cancelled mid-semester). In case you feel sick, e-mail Dr. Myose, obtain medical attention that day, and submit a copy of the note from the WSU Student Health Center or from a Kansas medical doctor that saw you on the day of the pre-test.] ODS approval (or medical doctor’s note if sick) will grant the alternative to in-person testing of substituting the final exam score for the pre-test score which would otherwise be a zero.

                    Weekly online quizzes will consist of calculation-type problems subdivided into smaller intermediate questions rather than a single final answer – this is different than the example problems. There will may also be some conceptual questions, primarily multiple choice in format. Students need to be aware that this is the method (answers entered using Microsoft Excel) used for online testing in weekly quizzes and the comprehensive final exam. Those who do not prefer such a testing method need to take another instructor’s course or take it during a different semester.

                  Life Drawing Studio

                  • ARTS341
                  • (CRN: 17040)

                  • Instructor:

                    Megan Ewert
                  • megan.ewert@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Required in-person content delivery or applied learning/lab, with some synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    In-person or online testing available

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    Will require textbook (Basic Human Anatomy: An Essential Visual Guide for Artists by Roberto Osti) that will be available in the school store on campus and a reserved copy of the text will be in the library. This is a figure drawing course--this means there will be nude models for anatomical reference on multiple days in class in order to further student knowledge and technical skills in drawing. Please be aware that nudity in art will be discussed and featured as a key subject matter in this course. Access to a digital camera and Adobe Photoshop required for personal assignments.

                    -Your familiarity with and access to Blackboard is needed because: 1) All course content delivery and communication items will be conducted using that application; and 2) Course testing events will likely also utilize that application.



                    -Due to the current status of classroom occupancy limits, initial lecture session delivery will be synchronous-remote via Zoom (possible transition to in-person delivery depending on institutional policy revisions related to changes in pandemic conditions).



                    -We cancelled the in-person teaching lab component of the BIOL 527 Comparative Vertebrate Anatomy course because we could not find or develop reasonable and safe ways to actually perform the extensive hands-on dissection activities and then conduct practical exams with the dissected animal specimens.                   Conservation Biology

                  • BIOL570
                  • (CRN: 14559)

                  • Instructor:

                    Francis Russell
                  • leland.russell@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Optional in-person content delivery, with synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    Required online testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    This course will include 1) optional, in-person content, 2) asynchronous on-line access to Panopto lectures and 3) synchronous on-line student oral presentations. This will be a blended hybrid course with remote/on-line testing. I want the content over which you will be tested to be available on-line for people who may be concerned about coming to campus, but I also want a robust, but optional, in-person component because I believe this enriches the educational experience and builds community (even if we are socially distanced).



                    Here are my ideas for how the in-person, asynchronous and synchronous components of the course will fit together.



                    Online / Remote components

                    - Lectures will be recorded in Panopto and made available for asynchronous viewing

                    - Tests will be administered on-line through Blackboard or as ‘take home’ assignments

                    - Student oral presentations will be presented on-line and synchronously



                    In-person components

                    - In-person class meetings will focus upon student questions concerning lectures, working practice problems, discussing additional case studies to further develop concepts, guest speakers through Zoom.

                    - In-person class meetings will occur on Mondays and Wednesdays, but not Fridays

                    - Article discussions will occur in-person. Discussions will involve 5 point assignments (to encourage reading the paper). Those assignments can be completed in a group if you attend the in-person discussion or individually if you choose not to attend.

                    Video lectures will be posted to view as your schedule permits. My BLAW 431 class will be conducted all on-line through Blackboard.  The class will be set up by weeks with all assignments and materials accessed through that week’s content folder in Blackboard.  In addition to reading the assigned text chapters each week, I will present a lecture on each chapter which will be a Youtube video of a Powerpoint presentation with audio voice over.  The Youtube video will have closed captions available and will be posted to view as students’ schedules permit.  I will also make the slides available to students in pdf format plus a Word note taker for use while watching the lectures.  Weekly quizzes, discussion boards, the mid-term and final will all be administered on-line via Blackboard.

                  Legal Environment of Business

                  • BLAW431
                  • (CRN: 11656)

                  • Instructor:

                    Frank Ojile
                  • fojile@prodigy.net (please put “B-Law Fall 2020” in the subject line)

                  • Planned Course Design

                  • Testing Type

                    Required in-person testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    I will try to make this class as much like a traditional in-person class as I can. Our classroom (107 CH) should permit about half of the class to attend at any one time, so I will split the class into two groups with half of the students attending on Tuesdays and the other half on Thursdays. Every class session will also be broadcast via a live Zoom meeting run from 107 CH so that students can still participate virtually on their off-days; these will be recorded so that all students can review the material later. Exams prior to Thanksgiving will be taken on campus, but may be scheduled over the course of a full week to provide the required social distancing. The final exam will be taken online after Thanksgiving.

My BLAW 431 class will be conducted all on-line through Blackboard.  The class will be set up by weeks with all assignments and materials accessed through that week’s content folder in Blackboard.  In addition to reading the assigned text chapters each week, I will present a lecture on each chapter which will be a Youtube video of a Powerpoint presentation with audio voice over.  The Youtube video will have closed captions available and will be posted to view as students’ schedules permit.  I will also make the slides available to students in pdf format plus a Word note taker for use while watching the lectures.  Weekly quizzes, discussion boards, the mid-term and final will all be administered on-line via Blackboard.

                  Counseling Techniques

                  • CESP824
                  • (CRN: 13542)

                  • Instructor:

                    Susan Bray
                  • susan.bray@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Optional in-person content delivery, with synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    Required online testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    CESP824:

                    This course allows students to learn and apply various counseling skills. The instructor will provide a lesson, describe and demonstrate a counseling technique, and the students will then practice those skills or techniques with one another in triads (counselor, client observer). The lecture will be delivered synchronously via zoom. Students will be divided into zoom practice rooms which will be viewable by the instructor for feedback. Starting in week 3, three students will meet on campus to practice skills with the instructor. Social distancing will be observed during on-campus triads and face coverings will be required. Students will meet in-person twice during the semester in their triads. Students who prefer not to come to campus will be accommodated. The course can be taught completely remotely if necessary in the case of a resurgence of the virus. Students will also have to counsel 2 individuals outside of class and provide a tape for feedback. This class requirement can be done remotely via zoom, swivl, or other means. Questions - feel free to email me!!!

                    For class, we are currently scheduled to meet every Thursday, 5-7:30. An official scheduled will be published when we get closer to the start of the semester. Meetings may often only last about 90 minutes, though again, students are expected to be available for longer meetings as needed.

                    This is a small group discussion-driven seminar course, which should adapt well to a synchronous online delivery through Zoom, though sessions will be recorded and available for asynchronous access as well. Students need access to reliable wifi.

                    Online students are required to have complete access to a functioning laptop or PC with internet capabilities. This laptop or computer must have Microsoft Word. If you do not have Microsoft Word on your PC or Laptop, Wichita State does provide free access to Microsoft Office 365 for students. Follow the instructions below to get Microsoft Office:

                    2. Click on Office 365 located on the “Home” tab

                    3. Follow the Office 365 wizard instructions

                  Manufacturing Methods and Materials I

                  • IME258
                  • (CRN: 15678)

                  • Instructor:

                    Vis Madhavan
                  • vis.madhavan@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Optional in-person content delivery, with synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    Required online testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    IME 258 Online Course Expectations:

                    1. Classes will be held live via Zoom. All students are expected to participate live, sharing their video. 10% of the course grade is for attendance, with one point taken off for each class the student is late or absent for.

                    a. Classes will likely be taught live from the classroom if the instructor is healthy, feels that no one's safety is being jeopardized, if institutional directives permit this, and if at least five students show up for these sessions. Otherwise they will be taught live from a remote location.

                    b. Anyone choosing to attend these classes in person needs to follow all WSU guidelines for doing so.

                    c. Additionally they should wear surgical masks at the minimum - bandannas or scarves will not be allowed to double as masks.

                    i. For masks with vents, the vent should be taped shut so one cannot expel aerosol particles violently upon sneezing or coughing.

                    d. Anyone attending a session in person will need to leave and not return if they cough or sneeze

                    i. If at all possible, they should leave the classroom before they sneeze or cough

                    ii. See below about also participating via Zoom

                    2. Even if a student chooses to attend class in person, they will need to participate via Zoom and share their video.

                    3. Office hours will be held via Zoom half an hour before and after class, and by zoom appointment at other times. These are optional to attend

                    a. If the class room is available during these times, office hours may also be held from the classroom per the same discretionary rules for classes

                    4. During assessments, students shouldn’t communicate with others or access disallowed resources (a phone, tablet, notes, books, etc.)

                    5. Students need to participate in online discussion forums

                    6. Need to allow instructor's recording of class meetings on Zoom

                    7. Need to learn material covered in lectures posted ahead of class time and be able to participate interactively during class via Zoom

                    8. Need to be professionally dressed and share your video and audio during class to participate in class

                    9. Need to control your surroundings and your microphone (which can be muted during times when you are not speaking) so that the class is not distracted or disrupted by you

                    10. Appropriate accommodations for students with disabilities will be made by the Office of Disability Services





                    Computer technology requirements:

                    1. A desktop or laptop PC (preferred) or a Mac with a good webcam, microphone, headphones, and a good internet connection are required to take assessments (unit tests and the final exam)

                    a. The laptop will also need at least 1GB of available storage.

                    2. You will use a special browser that you will need to be able to install on your laptop, the Respondus LockDown Browser (RLDB)

                    a. You can download and install this through links provided on BlackBoard. The first time you take a "Monitor"d test, you will be asked to permit your device to be accessed through the firewall.

                    3. You will need to follow the instructions below to take the test, which include recording yourself (audio and visual, including your surroundings, without overlaying any false background).

                    4. You will need a printer that you can use to print some assessment questions, write your answers in the provided spaces, and scan and upload the question and answer sheets





                    Instructions for recording yourself during the assessments:

                    You need to plan on spending 10 additional minutes for each assessment, to close all other applications and launch RLDB.



                    Students are expected to secure a suitable location for the duration of the exam, where they will be alone without anyone nearby to either disturb or assist you in any way.



                    Assessments, including several unit tests and a final exam, will be administered via the "Respondus LockDown Browser with Monitor". This uses AI to classify the student's behavior during the exam and alert instructors to possible irregularities during the exam and makes it easy to review the recording taken during the exam. Even otherwise, you should assume that instructors will review the videos of each of the tests. The principle is to ensure the fairness of online exams, by approximating the level of confidence and monitoring that we would have in an in-person exam.



                    1. RLDB will be used to access Blackboard, navigate to the assessment and launch it.

                    2. During the "Webcam Check" step, please say your name out loud and that you are taking Unit Test #_

                    3. Follow all the other instructions, ensuring you show your MyWSU ID such that we can match your face to that in the ID

                    a. Show a full 360 degree view of your surroundings. This should convince us that no course materials or the textbook or other electronic devices are accessible, that can be used to access information or communicate with others.

                    b. You may consult one handwritten double-sided sheet of notes, only for the final exam. This should be prepared by you and should be scanned and uploaded along with your answer sheets.

                    4. In the facial detection step (Step 8), position the webcam enough distance away from you so that in addition to your face, your desk/work area is also visible.

                    a. Place your phone face down beside your work area, within the view of the camera recording so we can be sure that you don’t use it during the exam

                    b. Throughout the assessment, your hands, the question/answer sheet, and your phone facing down should be visible to the camera

                    c. A desk that is about 2.5 feet deep should be sufficient to permit your laptop's webcam to record yourself and your work space. If not, you will need to use an external webcam placed where it can record your face and your work area.

                    5. Once you access the assessment, if the instructions ask you to print it out, do so and use that as the answer sheet. If you do not have a printer beside you, you may write your answers on a plain sheet of paper, but will need to reproduce a portion of the question to be sure we know what question you are answering, and reproduce any tables and figures you are asked to complete or annotate.

                    6. Throughout the assessment your hands, answer sheet, and the phone facing down should be visible to the camera.

                    7. If an interruption occurs, briefly explain what happened by speaking directly to your webcam.

                    8. After completing the exam, use your phone to scan or take pictures of your answer sheet and upload that to Blackboard using the phone.

                    9. Recording should continue until after you are done with the exam, and include yourself scanning the answer sheet with an app on your phone and uploading your work to Blackboard via your phone.

                    a. This means that in the video we will see the students submitting their assignment.

                    10. Speak into the webcam "I have completed the exam and uploaded the answer sheet at _____ (time)".

                    11. Submit the exam for grading. You can then close down RLB and leave.





                    Failing to meet these tech expectations means forfeiting one's assessment score; thus it is advisable that if you know you will not be able to satisfy these requirements you will have to drop the class.

This uses AI to classify the student's behavior during the exam and alert instructors to possible irregularities during the exam and makes it easy to review the recording taken during the exam. Even otherwise, you should assume that instructors will review the videos of each of the tests. The principle is to ensure the fairness of online exams, by approximating the level of confidence and monitoring that we would have in an in-person exam.



                    1. RLDB will be used to access Blackboard, navigate to the assessment and launch it.

                    2. During the "Webcam Check" step, please say your name out loud and that you are taking Unit Test #_

                    3. Follow all the other instructions, ensuring you show your MyWSU ID such that we can match your face to that in the ID

                    a. Show a full 360 degree view of your surroundings. This should convince us that no course materials or the textbook or other electronic devices are accessible, that can be used to access information or communicate with others.

                    b. You may consult one handwritten double-sided sheet of notes, only for the final exam. This should be prepared by you and should be scanned and uploaded along with your answer sheets.

                    4. In the facial detection step (Step 8), position the webcam enough distance away from you so that in addition to your face, your desk/work area is also visible.

                    a. Place your phone face down beside your work area, within the view of the camera recording so we can be sure that you don’t use it during the exam

                    b. Throughout the assessment, your hands, the question/answer sheet, and your phone facing down should be visible to the camera

                    c. A desk that is about 2.5 feet deep should be sufficient to permit your laptop's webcam to record yourself and your work space. If not, you will need to use an external webcam placed where it can record your face and your work area.

                    5. Once you access the assessment, if the instructions ask you to print it out, do so and use that as the answer sheet. If you do not have a printer beside you, you may write your answers on a plain sheet of paper, but will need to reproduce a portion of the question to be sure we know what question you are answering, and reproduce any tables and figures you are asked to complete or annotate.

                    6. Throughout the assessment your hands, answer sheet, and the phone facing down should be visible to the camera.

                    7. If an interruption occurs, briefly explain what happened by speaking directly to your webcam.

                    8. After completing the exam, use your phone to scan or take pictures of your answer sheet and upload that to Blackboard using the phone.

                    9. Recording should continue until after you are done with the exam, and include yourself scanning the answer sheet with an app on your phone and uploading your work to Blackboard via your phone.

                    a. This means that in the video we will see the students submitting their assignment.

                    10. Speak into the webcam "I have completed the exam and uploaded the answer sheet at _____ (time)".

                    11. Submit the exam for grading. You can then close down RLB and leave.





                    Failing to meet these tech expectations means forfeiting one's assessment score; thus it is advisable that if you know you will not be able to satisfy these requirements you will have to drop the class.

                    IME 758 Online Course Expectations:

                    1. Classes and lab sessions will be held in-person, and also simultaneously live via Zoom. All students are expected to participate in-person and live, sharing their video. 10% of the course grade is for attendance, with one point taken off for each class the student is late or absent for.

                    a. Classes will be taught live from the classroom if the instructor is healthy, feels that no one's safety is being jeopardized, if institutional directives permit this, and if at least five students show up for these sessions. Otherwise they will be taught live from a remote location.

                    b. Anyone attending these classes in person needs to follow all WSU guidelines for doing so.

                    c. Additionally they should wear surgical masks at the minimum - bandannas or scarves will not be allowed to double as masks.

                    i. For masks with vents, the vent should be taped shut so one cannot expel aerosol particles violently upon sneezing or coughing.

                    d. Anyone attending a session in person will need to leave and not return if they cough or sneeze

                    i. If at all possible, they should leave the classroom before they sneeze or cough

                    ii. See below about also participating via Zoom

                    2. Even if a student attends class in person, they will need to participate via Zoom and share their video.

                    3. Office hours will be held via Zoom half an hour before and after class, and by zoom appointment at other times. These are optional to attend

                    a. If the class room is available during these times, office hours may also be held from the classroom per the same discretionary rules for classes

                    4. During assessments, students shouldn’t communicate with others or access disallowed resources (a phone, tablet, notes, books, etc.)

                    5. Students need to participate in online discussion forums

                    6. Need to allow instructor's recording of class meetings on Zoom

                    7. Need to learn material covered in lectures posted ahead of class time and be able to participate interactively during class via Zoom

                    8. Need to be professionally dressed and share your video and audio during class to participate in class

                    9. Need to control your surroundings and your microphone (which can be muted during times when you are not speaking) so that the class is not distracted or disrupted by you

                    10. Appropriate accommodations for students with disabilities will be made by the Office of Disability Services



                    Computer technology requirements:

                    1. A desktop or laptop PC (preferred) or a Mac with a good webcam, microphone, headphones, and a good internet connection are required to take assessments (unit tests and the final exam)

                    a. The laptop will also need at least 1GB of available storage.

                    2. You will use a special browser that you will need to be able to install on your laptop, the Respondus LockDown Browser (RLDB)

                    a. You can download and install this through links provided on BlackBoard. The first time you take a "Monitor"d test, you will be asked to permit your device to be accessed through the firewall.

                    3. You will need to follow the instructions below to take the test, which include recording yourself (audio and visual, including your surroundings, without overlaying any false background).

                    4. You will need a printer that you can use to print some assessment questions, write your answers in the provided spaces, and scan and upload the question and answer sheets



                    Instructions for recording yourself during the assessments:

                    You need to plan on spending 10 additional minutes for each assessment, to close all other applications and launch RLDB.

                  Introduction to the History of Mathematics

                  • MATH531
                  • (CRN: 10840)

                  • Instructor:

                    John Hammond
                  • hammond@math.wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Optional in-person content delivery, with synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    In-person or online testing available

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    Hello prospective student!



                    Did you know that Italians in the 1500s settled personal disputes by challenging eachother to solve math problems?



                    Did you know that the Mayans would have a person dressed up as The God of Zero and have him ritually executed by having their jaw cut out? (Kaplan, 2000)



                    Did you know the Pythagorean Theorem wasn't discovered by Pythagoras? And that Pythagoras wasn't a mathematician? And that he was a cult leader?



                    This is a class where you'll learn about this and so much more. But if you're reading this, you probably are already planning to enroll in the class. Let's talk about the specifics:



                    - (Required) We'll meet online via video conferencing at our regularly scheduled class times (TR 4:00-5:15)

                    - (Required) Textbook to purchase is Math Through the Ages, Second Expanded Edition (ISBN 978-1-93951-212-3)

                    - other readings (free supplemental textbooks, pdfs, etc) will be posted to Blackboard / Discussion forum

                    - Required technology:

                    -- Access to high speed internet to do video conferencing at set times

                    -- Ability to record video presentations (via zoom, cell phone, etc)

                    - There will be no tests.

                    - There will be a lot of reading

                    - There will be a lot of writing

                    - We'll read the textbook cover-to-cover and individually do a lot of reading for three research papers.

                  Fundamentals of Finance

                  • MBA803
                  • (CRN: 14541)

                  • Instructor:

                    Stan Longhofer
                  • stan.longhofer@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Fully remote, synchronous delivery (HYB) - not a true hybrid course

                  • Testing Type

                    In-person or online testing available

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    This class combines the fully-online and the hybrid-online sections of MBA 803. Each week there will be a homework assignment that will be due on Sunday night. On Monday evenings at 7:05 I will have a live Zoom review session where I will go through the homework, expand on the ideas from the previous week's video lessons and answer any questions you have about the material. These sessions are important, because I will be discussing ideas that weren't necessarily fleshed out in the lesson videos. If you cannot join us live, don't worry; I will record the sessions as well and post them on Blackboard so that you can review the session later. There will be two exams and students may take them on-campus (times TBD), at a Testing Center (WSU or other), or proctored online via ProctorU.

                  Health Assessment

                  • NURS344
                  • (CRN: 14894)

                  • Instructor:

                    Mary E Faragher
                  • mary.faragher@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Required in-person content delivery or applied learning/lab, with some synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    In-person or online testing available

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    All exams administered, via computer, throughout the nursing program. Students must possess knowledge of their own device. This includes, but is not limited to:

                    ● How to connect to WSU’s secured and guest internet.

                    ● How to use Microsoft 365 (available to students free of charge).

                    ● How to use multiple web browsers (Firefox, Chrome, Edge, Safari, etc.).

                    ● How to download and install software. Caution: updates are not always compatible with software, check before downloading.

                    ● How to update your device as needed.

                    ● How to manage your security suite.

                    ● How to troubleshoot your device.

                    ● How to adjust your power settings to avoid the laptop sleeping or hibernate during an exam.

                    ● How to assess your device to ensure it is in good working order.

                    ● Bringing a device that has a fully charged battery and your power supply to class.

                    ● Having quick access to contact IT support for all programs used. Students are responsible for contacting IT for any troubleshooting needs.

                    ● How to navigate Blackboard learning management system. Students should contact WSU OneStop for assistance in using Blackboard.

                    ● Be an administrator on your device.

                  Research Methods in Psychology

                  • PSY311
                  • (CRN: 11380)

                  • Instructor:

                    Lisa Kline (Vangsness)
                  • lisa.vangsness@gmail.com

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Fully remote, synchronous delivery (HYB) - not a true hybrid course

                  • Testing Type

                    Required online testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    Course content will be delivered online. The lecture portion of the course will involve asynchronous lectures and synchronous bi-monthly meetings. The lab portion of the course will involve asynchronous lectures and optional synchronous instruction. Assignments will be submitted through Blackboard and video content will be provided in multiple formats (e.g., streaming, MP4, transcripts) to ease learning across a variety of platforms. To be successful in the course, students will need access to remote technology (i.e., a laptop and stable internet connection) and have Microsoft 365 or Mac Pages downloaded onto their computers. A subscription to IBM SPSS will be provided to students.

                  Marriage and Families

                  • SOC315
                  • (CRN: 11525)

                  • Instructor:

                    Jodie Hertzog
                  • jodie.hertzog@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Optional in-person content delivery, with synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    Required online testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    Course format:

                    For Fall, Sociology 315: Marriage & Families will be designed to integrate a combination of mostly asynchronous (online self-paced) learning modules with the potential for periodic enrichment oriented synchronous (i.e., accessed through Zoom or potentially face-to-face) class periods scattered across the semester. For example, a planned synchronous class period may feature a guest speaker or engaging in an applied activity or may have you select out of a list of identified university of community based events, speakers or activities that could enrich your learning experience as well as fit your personal interests and/or schedule. Note: synchronous learning experiences will NOT be weekly occurrences and any synchronous course meetings facilitated by Dr. Hertzog will occur during the originally scheduled course period (i.e., on a M or W, 9:30 - 10:45 am). Information for accessing any scheduled Zoom meetings will be provided on Blackboard.



                    Needed Technology:

                    Given that the meaning of “hybrid” for this course relies heavily on an online learning environment, students will need to have access to a device, preferably a computer, with internet and audio/video capability in order to access the provided learning modules on Blackboard including the ability to view and access online videos, readings (including PDF documents), & other related learning materials. All assignments and other learning assessments will be completed and/or submitted via Blackboard. Students will need to be able to access Microsoft Office programs (particularly Word & PPT) which are available through the university’s Microsoft 365 license free of charge to students. Finally, students will need to be able to access Zoom. Thus, access to a webcam is preferred but not required.

                  Theatre History I

                  • THEA623
                  • (CRN: 10382)

                  • Instructor:

                    Julie Longhofer
                  • julie.longhofer@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Required in-person content delivery or applied learning/lab, with some synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    Required in-person testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    Students will learn the principles of theatre history by means of lecture and discussion, following the Brockett textbook. Emphasis will be placed on the contemporary art of interpreting classical pieces of the drama. After analysis of historical trends and dramaturgy from each era, students will be responsible for applying their knowledge to contemporary productions as, for example, a literary manager, designer or director might do. The majority of students'weekly work will include reading plays and researching modern productions of classical productions. Class discussions will be stimulating and lively.

                  First Year Seminar: Discover Humanity - Honors

                  • WSUN102D
                  • (CRN: 14808)

                  • Instructor:

                    Kimberly Engber
                  • kimberly.engber@wichita.edu

                  • Planned Course Design

                    Optional in-person content delivery, with synchronous remote delivery (HYB)

                  • Testing Type

                    Required online testing

                  • Suggested technology recommendations or other information

                    Each student should have access to internet and a computer or laptop to be prepared for and successful in this course. Most course materials including reading will be available online. Discussions are planned to take place in small groups on alternate days in person and as a whole class online during class time for the first 8 weeks of the semester. During the second eight weeks, students will be working on independent research in addition to assigned course reading and will meet remotely or in-person with the instructor, remotely with research groups and remotely for class discussion. Quizzes will be online. Essays and writing assignments will be turned in through Blackboard.
